Twitter Sentiment Analysis¶

Step 1 : Data Collection¶

  • Tweet data of 2 handles #demonetization & #notebandhi was extracted

Step 2 : Data Processing - Cleansing¶

  • Cleanse the data (removing special characters, lemmatization etc.)

Step 3 : Execute Sentiment Analysis¶

  • Sentiment analysis was performed on the cleansed data, to classify if each of the document (news paper content) is positive, neutral or negative sentiment
  • Calculating the sentiment based on the number of times the tweet has been retweeted and favorites

Step 4: Analysis 1: Sentiment swings from Nov-2016 till Mar-2018¶

  • Summarize the sentiment by date & month

Step 5 : Wordcloud & Frequency distribution of the overall tweet text corpus¶

  • Overall corpus was split into training and test data. Wordcloud showed some code syntax to be present, which was cleansed.
  • Wordcloud was generated on the overall text corpus
  • Frequency distribution of overall words in the text corpus was generated

Data Collection¶

  • Data was collected using two Python packages

https://github.com/HagopB/twitter_scrap

https://github.com/tomkdickinson/Twitter-Search-API-Python

  • Using the above packages, demonetization tweets were collected year-wise using the following commands. The hash-tags that were used were #demonetization & #notebandhi

python scrap.py --scrap_type="slice" --search_query_list="#demonetization,#notebandhi" --tweets_since="2016-11-01" --tweets_until="2016-12-31"

python scrap.py --scrap_type="slice" --search_query_list="#demonetization,#notebandhi" --tweets_since="2017-11-01" --tweets_until="2017-12-31"

python scrap.py --scrap_type="slice" --search_query_list="#demonetization,#notebandhi" --tweets_since="2018-11-01" --tweets_until="2018-12-31"

  • The output is a pickle-compressed file. The tweets from the pickled file, were unpickled and loaded to a csv file

for x in os.listdir(DATA_PATH):
    if x.endswith('.pkl'):
        f_name = os.path.join(DATA_PATH,x)
        file = open(f_name, 'rb')
        data = pickle.load(file)
        file.close()
        for item in data: 
            try:
                datex = int(int(str(item['created_at']).split('.')[0])/1000)
                #print(datex)

                                'created_at':datetime.fromtimestamp(datex),
                                'retweets':item['retweets'],
                                'favorites':item['favorites']
                               },ignore_index=True)

Cleansing/Lemmatizing Data for Further Sentiment Analysis¶

  • Removing links from the tweet content

  • Removing Special Characters & double spacing

In [4]:
import re
df2['text']=df2['text'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'^https?:\/\/.*[\r\n]*', ' ', x.lower()))
df2['text']=df2['text'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'(.*\.)?twitter\.com\/[A-z 0-9 _]+\/?', ' ', x.lower()))
df2['text']=df2['text'].apply(lambda x: re.sub('[!@#$:).;,?&]', '', x.lower()))
df2['text'] = df2['text'].apply(lambda x: re.sub('  ', ' ', x))

  • Step 1 : Using the WordNet Lemmatizer for finding the words/sentences

  • Step 2 : Using a TfidfVectorizer to vectorize the data

  • Step 3 : Vectorized Data was passed to SentimentIntensityAnalyzer, for every newspaper content.

  • Step 4 : Storing the compound polarity, neutral, positive, negative polarity scores & classifying them into sentiment types.

In [5]:
df2['text_lem'] = [''.join([WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize(re.sub('[^A-Za-z]', ' ', line)) for line in lists]).strip() for lists in df2['text']]       
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_df=0.5,max_features=10000,min_df=10,stop_words='english',use_idf=True)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(df2['text_lem'].str.upper())
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
df2['sentiment_compound_polarity']=df2.text_lem.apply(lambda x:sid.polarity_scores(x)['compound'])
df2['sentiment_neutral']=df2.text_lem.apply(lambda x:sid.polarity_scores(x)['neu'])
df2['sentiment_negative']=df2.text_lem.apply(lambda x:sid.polarity_scores(x)['neg'])
df2['sentiment_pos']=df2.text_lem.apply(lambda x:sid.polarity_scores(x)['pos'])
df2['sentiment_type']=''
df2.loc[df2.sentiment_compound_polarity>0,'sentiment_type']='POSITIVE'
df2.loc[df2.sentiment_compound_polarity==0,'sentiment_type']='NEUTRAL'
df2.loc[df2.sentiment_compound_polarity<0,'sentiment_type']='NEGATIVE'

Sentiment Compound Polarity¶

  • if a given tweet has been tweeted multiple times, the polarity of the sentiment would be multiplied the number of times and doubled
  • if a given tweet has been marked as favorite multiple times, the polarity of the sentiment would be multiplied the number of times the tweet it has been marked favorite
In [7]:
i = 0 
df2['calculated_score'] = 0.0
for i in range(len(df2)):
    if i % 1000 == 0:
        print(i)
    df2['calculated_score'][i] = df2['sentiment_compound_polarity'] [i]+ \
                                 (df2['sentiment_compound_polarity'] [i]* df2['favorites'][i]) + \
                                 (df2['sentiment_compound_polarity'][i] * df2['retweets'][i] * 2)

def wordcloud_draw(data, color = 'black'):
    words = ' '.join(data)
    cleaned_word = " ".join([word for word in words.split()
                            if 'http' not in word
                                and not word.startswith('@')
                                and not word.startswith('#')
                                and word != 'RT'
                            ])
    wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=STOPWORDS,
                      background_color=color,
                      width=2500,
                      height=2000
                     ).generate(cleaned_word)
    plt.figure(1,figsize=(13, 13))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()
    
print("Positive words")
wordcloud_draw(train_pos,'white')
print("Negative words")
wordcloud_draw(train_neg)

from nltk.corpus import stopwords
tweets = []
stopwords_set = set(stopwords.words("english"))

for index, row in df_bow.iterrows():
    words_filtered = [e.lower() for e in row.text_lem.split() if len(e) >= 3]
    words_cleaned = [word for word in words_filtered
        if 'http' not in word
        and not word.startswith('@')
        and not word.startswith('#')
        and word != 'RT']
    words_without_stopwords = [word for word in words_cleaned if not word in stopwords_set]
    tweets.append((words_without_stopwords,row.sentiment_type))

# Extracting word features
def get_words_in_tweets(tweets):
    all = []
    for (words, sentiment) in tweets:
        all.extend(words)
    return all

def get_word_features(wordlist):
    wordlist = nltk.FreqDist(wordlist)
    features = wordlist.keys()
    return features
w_features = get_word_features(get_words_in_tweets(tweets))

def extract_features(document):
    document_words = set(document)
    features = {}
    for word in w_features:
        features['contains(%s)' % word] = (word in document_words)
    return features
